  "prompt": "What is the difference between a possum and an opossum?",
  "response": "The terms \"possum\" and \"opossum\" are often used interchangeably, but they refer to different animals from distinct regions and families:\n\n1. **Opossum**:\n   - **Scientific Name**: Didelphidae family (specifically the common Virginia opossum, *Didelphis virginiana*).\n   - **Habitat**: Native to North America.\n   - **Appearance**: They have a pointed snout, a prehensile tail (used for grasping), and a mix of grayish-white fur. They are marsupials, meaning females carry their young in a pouch.\n   - **Behavior**: Known for \"playing dead\" (thanatosis) when threatened.\n\n2. **Possum**:\n   - **Scientific Name**: Phalangeriformes family.\n   - **Habitat**: Native to Australia, New Guinea, and Sulawesi.\n   - **Appearance**: Possums have a more rounded snout, bushy tails, and vary in size and color. They are also marsupials.\n   - **Behavior**: Generally tree-dwelling and nocturnal.\n\nThe confusion arises because early English settlers in North America thought the opossum resembled the Australian possum, leading to the colloquial use of \"possum\" for both. However, they are not closely related.",
